      "type": "explanation",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "title",
          "value": "The Universal Classifier: go3"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "In English, we say 'one person' or 'two books'. In Cantonese, you can't just put a number in front of a noun. You need a <strong>Classifier</strong> (also called a measure word) in the middle."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "The most common classifier is <strong>個</strong> (go3). It is used for people and many other general objects. The basic structure is: <br><strong>Number + Classifier + Noun</strong>"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "一個",
          "romanization": "jat1 go3",
          "translation": "One (of something)"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "一個人",
          "romanization": "jat1 go3 jan4",
          "translation": "One person"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "兩個學生",
          "romanization": "loeng5 go3 hok6 saang1",
          "translation": "Two students (Remember to use 'loeng5' here!)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "exerciseId": "4.2.2"
    },
    {
      "type": "unscramble",
      "exerciseId": "4.2.3"
    },
    {
      "type": "dialog",
      "lines": [
        {
          "speaker": "A",
          "cantonese": "你哋幾多個人呀？",
          "romanization": "nei5 dei6 gei2 do1 go3 jan4 aa3?",
          "translation": "How many of you (people) are there?"
        },
        {
          "speaker": "B",
          "cantonese": "我哋三個人。",
          "romanization": "ngo5 dei6 saam1 go3 jan4.",
          "translation": "We are three people."
        },
        {
          "speaker": "A",
          "cantonese": "好呀。",
          "romanization": "hou2 aa3.",
          "translation": "Okay."
        }
      ]
    },
